What is a Coroutine?

A coroutine is a special type of function that can pause its execution, 
save its current state, and resume later from where it left off.

Unlike a normal function:

A normal function runs from start to finish in one call.
A coroutine can stop in the middle, return control to the caller, and continue later.

Think of it like reading a book:

Normal function: Read the whole book in one sitting.
Coroutine: Read one chapter, place a bookmark, do something else, then continue from the bookmark later.

Three Coroutine Keywords
    Keyword	    Purpose
    co_return	Finish the coroutine and optionally return a value.
    co_yield	Produce a value and suspend execution.
    co_await	Suspend until another asynchronous operation is ready.

Common Use Cases
    Generators (produce values one by one)
    Asynchronous I/O (networking, file operations)
    Game loops (scripted sequences, animations)
    Streaming large datasets
    Task schedulers
    High-performance servers

Coroutines let you write code that looks sequential while still allowing execution to pause and resume efficiently, 
without blocking the thread.